 1306–about 1355","1290–1369":"1290–1369","1305–1356":"1305–1356","1306–1355":"1306–1355","1310–1374":"1310–1374","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1300–1361":"1300–1361","1325–1378":"1325–1378","1330–1402":"1330–1402","1334–1378":"1334–1378","1268–1360":"1268–1360","1270–1319":"1270–1319","prima del 1290":"before 1290","1330":"1330","1374":"1374","1361":"1361","Abt 1334":"about 1334","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","1402":"1402","1325":"1325","1369":"1369","1268":"1268","1334":"1334","1378":"1378","1356":"1356","about 1306":"about 1306","1300":"1300","1355":"1355","Est 1325":"about 1325","1310":"1310","about 1355":"about 1355","1319":"1319","1306":"1306","Mantova, Mantova, Lombardy, Italy":"Mantova, Mantova, Lombardy, Italy","Öttingen, Schwaben, Bavaria, Germany":"Swabia, Bavaria, Germany","Italy":"Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Francesca","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Frances  , now widely used in the English-speaking world. Originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’, it was bestowed from the 13th century onwards in honour of  St Francis  of Assisi. It has also been used independently as an English name. Its most famous bearer was  Francesca di Rimini , daughter of  Giovanni da Polenta , Count of Ravenna. A legendary beauty, she was betrothed by her father to the misshapen Giovanni Malatesta, Lord of Rimini, in return for military support. Malatesta's good-looking younger brother, Paolo, acted as his proxy in the betrothal, but Francesca and he fell in love. They were discovered, and put to death by  Malatesta  in  1289 . Their tragedy is enshrined in the Fifth Canto of  Dante's  Inferno, as well as in several other works of literature and in a symphonic fantasy by  Tchaikovsky ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gonzaga","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some chara